          In 1905, a 26-year-old patent clerk named Albert Einstein published a paper that would forever change our understanding of the universe. His theory of relativity challenged centuries of established physics and introduced a new way of thinking about space, time, and gravity.
        </p>
        
        <h2>The Special Theory of Relativity</h2>
        <p>
          Einstein's first breakthrough came with his Special Theory of Relativity, published in his paper "On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies." This theory was built on two fundamental principles:
        </p>
        
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>The Principle of Relativity:</strong> The laws of physics are the same in all inertial reference frames (frames moving at constant velocity relative to each other).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The Constancy of the Speed of Light:</strong> Light always travels at the same speed (approximately 299,792,458 meters per second in a vacuum), regardless of the motion of the light source or the observer.
          </li>
        </ol>
        
        <p>
          These seemingly simple principles led to profound consequences, including:
        </p>
        
        <ul>
          <li>Time dilation: Moving clocks run slower relative to stationary ones</li>
          <li>Length contraction: Objects in motion appear shorter along their direction of travel</li>
          <li>Relativistic mass: An object's mass increases as its velocity approaches the speed of light</li>
          <li>The equivalence of mass and energy, expressed in the famous equation E=mc²</li>
        </ul>
        
        <div class="bg-primary-50 dark:bg-primary-900/30 p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-primary-500 my-8">
