            "When you sit with a nice girl for two hours, it seems like two minutes; when you sit on a hot stove for two minutes, it seems like two hours. That's relativity."
            <footer class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">— Albert Einstein</footer>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
        
        <h2>The General Theory of Relativity</h2>
        <p>
          Ten years later, in 1915, Einstein published his General Theory of Relativity, which expanded on Special Relativity to include gravity. This theory presented a revolutionary concept: gravity is not a force, as Newton had described it, but rather a curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          Key insights from General Relativity include:
        </p>
        
        <ul>
          <li>Spacetime is a four-dimensional fabric that can be warped by massive objects</li>
          <li>Objects move along geodesics (the shortest paths) in curved spacetime</li>
          <li>Light rays follow curved paths when passing near massive objects</li>
          <li>Time passes slower in stronger gravitational fields</li>
        </ul>
        
        <figure class="my-8">
          <img 
            src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/5210252/pexels-photo-5210252.jpeg" 
            alt="Spacetime curvature illustration" 
            class="rounded-lg w-full"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">
            Illustration of spacetime curvature caused by a massive object
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        
        <h2>Experimental Confirmation</h2>
        <p>
          One of the remarkable aspects of Einstein's theories was that they made precise, testable predictions. Several key observations have confirmed the validity of relativity:
        </p>
        
        <h3>The Bending of Light</h3>
        <p>
          During a solar eclipse in 1919, astronomer Arthur Eddington observed that starlight was indeed bent as it passed near the sun, exactly as Einstein had predicted. This dramatic confirmation made Einstein internationally famous overnight.
        </p>
        
        <h3>Gravitational Redshift</h3>
        <p>
          Light emitted from a source in a strong gravitational field is shifted toward the red end of the spectrum when observed from a region of weaker gravity. This effect has been measured with high precision using atomic clocks at different altitudes.
        </p>
        
        <h3>Gravitational Waves</h3>
        <p>
          In 2015, the Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory (LIGO) detected gravitational waves—ripples in spacetime—produced by the collision of two black holes. This observation, coming exactly 100 years after Einstein's publication of General Relativity, provided stunning confirmation of the theory.
        </p>
        
        <h2>Practical Applications</h2>
        <p>
          Far from being merely theoretical, Einstein's relativity has numerous practical applications:
        </p>
        
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Global Positioning System (GPS):</strong> GPS satellites must account for both special and general relativistic effects to provide accurate positioning. Without these corrections, GPS would accumulate errors of about 10 kilometers per day!
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Particle Accelerators:</strong> The design of particle accelerators must account for relativistic effects as particles approach the speed of light.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Nuclear Energy:</strong> The famous equation E=mc² is the foundation for understanding nuclear reactions and the enormous energy released when mass is converted to energy.
          </li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>The Legacy of Relativity</h2>
        <p>
          Einstein's theories of relativity not only revolutionized physics but also had profound impacts on philosophy, literature, and popular culture. The concept that time and space are relative rather than absolute has influenced thinking far beyond scientific circles.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          Today, relativity remains a cornerstone of modern physics, serving as a foundation for understanding the universe on its largest scales. It works alongside quantum mechanics (which describes the universe at the smallest scales) as one of the two pillars of modern physics.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          The search for a unified theory that can reconcile these two frameworks—a "theory of everything"—continues to be one of the great quests of theoretical physics, carrying forward Einstein's legacy of bold, imaginative exploration of the fundamental nature of reality.
        </p>
        
        <div class="bg-secondary-50 dark:bg-secondary-900/30 p-6 rounded-lg my-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Key Concepts in Relativity</h3>
