            <li><strong>Spacetime:</strong> The four-dimensional continuum of space and time</li>
            <li><strong>Invariance:</strong> Physical laws remain the same across all reference frames</li>
            <li><strong>Mass-Energy Equivalence:</strong> Mass can be converted to energy and vice versa (E=mc²)</li>
            <li><strong>Spacetime Curvature:</strong> Massive objects cause spacetime to curve, which we experience as gravity</li>
            <li><strong>Light Cone:</strong> The path that light would take through spacetime, defining causally related events</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>
          Einstein's theories of relativity stand as one of the greatest intellectual achievements in human history, fundamentally altering our understanding of space, time, and gravity. From the bending of starlight to the precision of GPS, from black holes to gravitational waves, the predictions of relativity continue to be confirmed with remarkable accuracy.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          As we venture further into space and probe deeper into the fundamental nature of reality, Einstein's revolutionary insights continue to guide our understanding of the cosmos. His work reminds us of the power of human creativity and the profound beauty of the universe revealed through the lens of physics.
        </p>
